Germany, year zero
The 8th of May always reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was really a decisive moment in my life.
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our little street, in the western outskirts of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would return from the Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide like after my liberation from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
With the Nazis gone, the occupying powers had not yet set up an administration.
We were looting the neighborhood stores. I still have some volumes of Romantic poetry from a bookstore.
I was sixteen years old. The occupying forces were committing all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was directly transported from his prison to the center of Berlin, and charged with setting up - from scratch - the city's energy supply office.
For a while, there was no electricity, no transportation, and no organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans, it was a delicate matter, even if for our family it was undoubtedly a liberation in every sense of the word.
But for what to do it?
For what future?
" You must help, " my mother said to me.
Therefore, I offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food products to some distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card for "victim of fascism," while others wore a Iron Cross obtained for late military service.
Some were Eastern refugees, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, and almost all mourned the loss of loved ones.
However, this step did not last.
It is practically incredible, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered Germany's "economic miracle."
More precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between occupation powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and especially accompanied by a new form of oppression.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and inmates.
On the contrary, after a short period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections took place.
Democracy was not a mere slogan, and it relied on German traditions.
Certainly, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and each side wanted to consolidate "its" part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular merit being mentioned.
The first one is of an economic nature and is related to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy undoubtedly takes deeper root in an economic recovery context.
For this, above all, it takes initiative on the part of individuals who wish to put an end to a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with an initial capital.
The importance of American support through the Marshall Plan.
In the same way, the European Union has helped the formerly communist countries, and continues to accompany them in their endeavors.
The other lesson, of a moral nature, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials rendered the guilt of the Nazi leaders indisputable.
However, Germany has not embarked on its long journey by worrying about the past.
In fact, many have described Adenauer's years after 1949 as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi figures had remained in their positions.
In a way, the country was ignoring its past to move forward into the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and a political democracy, Germany has successfully faced its past.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other devastated countries therefore cause confusion.
However, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first the novelty, then an attempt to come to terms with the past.
In the end, it is a better method.
In Europe, May 8, 2005 is an occasion to look back at the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and therefore filled with hope.
